{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505629"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.82,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78988"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2460"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4459"},{"type":"tags","id":"4460"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78988"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents 40 minutes after an uncomplicated spontaneous vaginal delivery at term with gradually worsening lower abdominal pain and light-headedness. This is her third pregnancy and delivery. The third stage was prolonged, requiring multiple attempts at controlled cord traction to deliver the placenta, which appeared complete with intact membranes on inspection. Her previous pregnancies were uncomplicated. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in pain. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Active vaginal bleeding is observed with a pool of blood noted on the bed. Abdominal examination reveals a soft, boggy uterus palpable above the umbilicus. There is no mass protruding from the vagina. A fluid bolus of intravenous saline is being administered via a large-bore intravenous cannula and an indwelling urinary catheter has been inserted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the postpartum haemorrhage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine rupture","Uterine inversion","Uterine atony","Retained placenta","Cervical laceration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a primary postpartum haemorrhage. The finding of a soft, boggy uterus palpable above the umbilicus with active bleeding is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Euterine atony\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common cause of primary postpartum haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine inversion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a round mass protruding from the vagina and an inability to palpate the uterine fundus abdominally. While prolonged cord traction (as occurred in this case) is a risk factor, there is no mass visible in the vagina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine rupture\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents during labour with sudden onset severe abdominal pain and fetal compromise. It is more common in women with previous caesarean sections, which this patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetained placenta\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as the placenta was delivered and noted to be complete with intact membranes. While retained products can cause ongoing bleeding, the soft boggy uterus points more towards atony as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical laceration\u003C/strong\u003E can occur during delivery and cause significant bleeding, but would not explain the boggy uterus. Additionally, cervical lacerations are less common than uterine atony.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe 4 T\u0027s (Tone, Tissue, Trauma, Thrombin) provide a systematic approach to diagnosing postpartum haemorrhage. Initial management includes bimanual compression to stimulate uterine contractions, fluid resuscitation, and administration of uterotonics such as oxytocin, ergometrine, and carboprost. If bleeding continues despite medical management, examination under anaesthesia may be required to exclude other causes and consider surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Uterine atony is the most common cause of primary postpartum haemorrhage, presenting with a soft, boggy uterus and active bleeding.","The 4 T\u0027s (Tone, Tissue, Trauma, Thrombin) provide a systematic approach to diagnosing the cause of postpartum haemorrhage.","Initial management of postpartum haemorrhage includes bimanual compression, fluid resuscitation, and uterotonics."],"references":["Ende HB, Lozada MJ, Chestnut DH, et al. Risk Factors for Atonic Postpartum Hemorrhage: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. Obstet Gynecol 2021;137:305. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33417319/","Mu\u00f1oz M, Stensballe J, Ducloy-Bouthors AS, et al. Patient blood management in obstetrics: prevention and treatment of postpartum haemorrhage. A NATA consensus statement. Blood Transfus 2019;17:112. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30865585/","WOMAN: reducing maternal deaths with tranexamic acid. Lancet. 2017 May 27;389(10084):2081. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(17)31111-X/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64337"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T12:57:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T12:57:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2460"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78988"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships